Problem Statement¶

In this problem, we would like to predict whether a credit card client will default or not in the coming month or not, based on their demographic factors, credit data, history of payment, and bill statements in Taiwan from April 2005 to September 2005.

We are given a data set UCI_Credit_Card.csv which has 30,000 observations and 25 fields.

Data Field Description¶

Below shows the description of each of the fields,

Variable Description
ID ID of each client
LIMIT_BAL Amount of given credit in NT dollars (includes individual and family/supplementary credit)
SEX Gender (1=male, 2=female)
EDUCATION (1=graduate school, 2=university, 3=high school, 4=others, 5=unknown, 6=unknown)
MARRIAGE Marital status (1=married, 2=single, 3=others)
AGE Age in years
PAY_0 Repayment status in September, 2005 (-2=No consumption, -1=pay duly, 0=The use of revolving credit, 1=payment delay for one month, 2=payment delay for two months, ..., 8=payment delay for eight months, 9=payment delay for nine months and above)
PAY_2 Repayment status in August, 2005 (scale same as above)
PAY_3 Repayment status in July, 2005 (scale same as above)
PAY_4 Repayment status in June, 2005 (scale same as above)
PAY_5 Repayment status in May, 2005 (scale same as above)
PAY_6 Repayment status in April, 2005 (scale same as above)
BILL_AMT1 Amount of bill statement in September, 2005 (NT dollar)
BILL_AMT2 Amount of bill statement in August, 2005 (NT dollar)
BILL_AMT3 Amount of bill statement in July, 2005 (NT dollar)
BILL_AMT4 Amount of bill statement in June, 2005 (NT dollar)
BILL_AMT5 Amount of bill statement in May, 2005 (NT dollar)

PAY_AMT1 Amount of previous payment in September, 2005 (NT dollar)

PAY_AMT4 Amount of previous payment in June, 2005 (NT dollar)

PAY_AMT6 Amount of previous payment in April, 2005 (NT dollar)
default.payment.next.month Default payment (1=yes, 0=no) (This will be our prediction target)

Initial Thoughts¶

PAY_X variable¶
  1. By skimming the PAY_X fields for the first few observations of the data, it was hard to make sense of what it means given the definitions of these variables provided on Kaggle. For example, We see that PAY_X for ID = 11 jumps from 0 in August to 2 in June. That is, the client clearing minimum payment in July was declared as "payment delay for two months" in August (one month later). It does not seem logical. Even worse, for ID = 1, PAY_X jumped from -1 in July to 2 in August i.e. The client who paid on time in the earlier month was reported as "payment delay for two months" in the following month. We also observed that for ID = 19 or ID = 20, the PAY_X is 1 even though the BILL_AMTX is 0. This implied that those clients never use their credit card (i.e. bill statement of 0 in BILL_AMT6 to BILL_AMT1). However, they are recorded to have a "payment delay for one month" in the last month, i.e. PAY_0 = 1 which does not make any sense.

We were thinking of dropping the 'PAY_X' variables due to the issues described above. But since we expect our target variable to be analogous to PAY_X variable in terms of a systematic error, we decided against dropping them completely. Nevertheless, we want to minimize the systematic error by engineering new features out of these ones.

  1. The name of one of the variables i.e. PAY_0 is inconsistent with the naming convention used by other variables in the dataset i.e. BILL_AMTX and PAY_AMTX. We therefore think it would be more suitable to name it as PAY_1 for consistency.

Therefore, we believe that there might be some problems in the data collection or data processing from the data creator. If possible, we would like to contact them (https://tw.linkedin.com/in/i-cheng-yeh-25ab2215, https://kamino.tru.ca/experts/home/main/bio.php?id=elien) for clarification before we could make good use of the PAY_X fields for our classification task.

Class Imbalance¶
  1. In reality, we would expect the clients to usually pay on time in order to avoid late penalties, and hence, would also expect most of the observations to have default.payment.next.month = 0. We therefore expect the dataset to have a class imbalance.

def get_cv_table_from_searchCV(searchCV, round=3):
    # Extract the best result from searchCV, e.g. RandomizedSearchCV
    best_result = pd.DataFrame(searchCV.cv_results_).query('rank_test_score == 1')
    best_result = best_result[[
        'mean_fit_time', 'std_fit_time',
        'mean_score_time', 'std_score_time',
        'mean_test_score', 'std_test_score',
        'mean_train_score', 'std_train_score'
    ]].T.reset_index()

    # Parse mean_xxxx and std_xxxx into 2 columns
    names = pd.DataFrame(best_result['index'].str.split('_').tolist())
    best_result['stat'] = names[0]
    best_result['type'] = names[1] + '_' + names[2]
    best_result = best_result.drop(columns='index')

    # Format
    best_result = best_result.pivot(columns='stat', index='type')
    best_result.columns = ['mean', 'std']
    best_result.index.name = None

    return best_result.round(round)

3. EDA ¶

rubric={viz,reasoning}

Perform exploratory data analysis on the train set.

Your tasks:

  1. Include at least two summary statistics and two visualizations that you find useful, and accompany each one with a sentence explaining it.
  2. Summarize your initial observations about the data.
  3. Pick appropriate metric/metrics for assessment.

Points: 6

  1. Our training dataset comprises 22,500 observations, encompassing 24 distinct features. Below are our observations:

    • Class imbalance is evident in the data with around 25% of default.payment.next.month = 1. Therefore, accuracy alone may not serve as an appropriate metric for evaluation.
    • While all columns are presented numerical, a closer examination reveals that some are better described as ordinal or categorical; e.g. sex, education & marriage
    • Across both classes, we observe a consistent distribution for all numerical features.
    • Notably, outliers are apparent especially in BILL_AMT, evident in the considerable disparity between the mean and median, as well as the notable standard deviation.
    • In the correlation matrix, a relatively high correlation is observed among the 'pay_' variables, suggesting that if an individual experiences a repayment delay in one period, there is a likelihood of encountering similar delays in subsequent periods
    • The 'bill_amount' variables exhibit correlations with the 'pay_' variables, reflecting the intuitive connection between increasing bills and delayed payments.
    • There is a noteworthy correlation among the bill statements across different years. This implies a consistent pattern or interdependence in the billing statements from one year to the next.

  2. It is pertinent to examine the distribution of the bill amount variable, with particular attention to negative and zero values. Negative amounts imply that the individual has not only settled their expenses but has also made additional payments. Meanwhile, a value of 0 suggests either the absence of any expenses or that the person has already completely paid off all incurred expenses.

  3. In alignment with our business case objectives, our primary focus is on minimizing false negatives, emphasizing Recall. However, recognizing the limitations of optimizing this metric in isolation, we plan to use the f1 score for hyperparameter optimization, and will place a higher importance on recall over precision when evaluating the models for more balanced and robust results.

def plot_histogram(df, col_name, maxbins): 
    """
    Plots the histogram of a numerical column in the dataset
    """
    plot = alt.Chart(df).mark_bar().encode(
        alt.X(col_name).type('quantitative').bin(maxbins=maxbins),
        y='count()',
        color=alt.Color('default\.payment\.next\.month').title('default.payment.next.month')
    ).properties(
        width=300,
        height=200
    )
    return plot

4. Feature engineering (Challenging)¶

rubric={reasoning}

Your tasks:

  1. Carry out feature engineering. In other words, extract new features relevant for the problem and work with your new feature set in the following exercises. You may have to go back and forth between feature engineering and preprocessing.

Points: 0.5

The Payment Coverage Ratio is a feature derived by dividing the feature PAY_AMT_{X-1} by BILL_AMT_{X}. This ratio describes the amount the person paid relative to their monthly bill amount. A ratio of 1 indicates a perfect score as they paid off their bill entirely. A ratio of 0 indicates that the person did not pay anything of the bill and is therefore the "worst" ratio. A person who paid more than their bill amount would have a ratio greater than 1. The special case here is when a person does not have any amount to pay for a certain month. This is indicated by the ratio 1 and therefore treated equally to someone with a perfect ratio. In our data set we call this new variables 'pay_to_bill'. For this newly created variable, we only include the average, standard deviation, and the ratio of average over standard deviation. This is to gauge overall behavior across all periods, with the anticipation that a significant deviation from this ratio is unlikely for a creditworthy customer.

PAY_X Cleaning and Binning¶

In [14]:
# Clean the column name
data['PAY_1'] = data['PAY_0']

# Bin the PAY_X: (-2, -1) -> duly; (0) -> credit; (1, 2, ..., 9) -> delay
for i in range(1, 7):
    data[f'PAY_{i}_split'] = np.where(
        data[f'PAY_{i}'] < 0, 'duly', 
        np.where(
            data[f'PAY_{i}'] == 0, 'credit',

        )

tmp = tmp.reset_index(['ID', 'value']).pivot(index='ID', columns='value').fillna(0).reset_index()
tmp.columns = ['ID', 'credit_count', 'delay_count', 'duly_count']

data = data.merge(tmp, how='left', on='ID')

As highlighted in the Initial Thoughts Section, we observed anomalous behavior in the PAY_ variables, indicative of a systematic error within these variables. To minimize this systematic error, we opt to categorize these variables by binning them into three groups based on their feature values. Value less than zero are labelled as 'duly', i.e. they pay on time. If the value is equal to zero, the person has cleared the minimum payment. All other value imply that there is a delay in payment. Out of these binned groups we build other 3 variables by counting the respective values, namely credit_count, delay_count and duly_count.

2. Summarize your results in terms of overfitting/underfitting and fit and score times. Can you beat the performance of the linear model?

LightGBM, XGBoost, and KNN models were employed for analysis. In regard to validation scores, all three models outperformed the linear model prior to hyperparameter optimization. However, they exhibited more pronounced overfitting compared to logistic regression, which had nearly equal train and validation scores. The disparity between train and validation scores for LightGBM and KNN is around 0.1, while XGBoost demonstrated more significant overfitting, achieving a test score of 0.455 and a training score of 0.624.

In terms of fit time, KNN was significantly faster and LightGBM was slower than logistic regression. XGBoost was the slowest with around 0.5 seconds average fit time compared to just over 0.1 seconds fit time achieved by the linear model. In terms of score time, the linear model was faster than all three models tried in this question (but only slightly lower than XGBoost and LightGBM) KNN emerged as the slowest model in terms of score time.

# Extract fitted transformer
fitted_preprocesor = best_lgbm_pipe.named_steps['columntransformer']

# Extract transformed features
enc_feat = []
for transformer in fitted_preprocesor.named_transformers_.values():
    if transformer == 'drop':
        continue
    enc_feat += transformer.get_feature_names_out().tolist()

# Transform X_test

    fitted_preprocesor.transform(X_test),

)

15. Your takeaway from the course (Challenging)¶

rubric={reasoning}

What is your biggest takeaway from this course?

Points: 0.25

Particularly interesting is the concept of SHAP values, which gives you an idea of the feature importance in an individual prediction. Thus, it is a great tool that complements permutation importance, which provides an overall picture of feature importance. There are also helpful visualizations for illustrating these tools.
